document.text: Panel B: Reduction in average dispersion
Panel C: Dispersion changes correlated with location changes
Panel D: Dispersion changes correlated with initial location
Panel E: Regional variation in location is small
See the text for a description of each panel. Each panel displays average results for 5,000 simulations,
adds regional differences in the initial location parameter, as well as dispersion pa-
rameters. That generates some bias. Finally, Panel E makes regions more similar in terms of
their location parameters. That leads to large biases.
The fundamental problem is similar to that in the case of the fraction affected design: the
treatment intensity variable used in the regression does not neatly map into the thought ex-
periment that intuitively identifies the causal effect of interest. Random shocks to location,
uncorrelated with dispersion parameters, provide good variation because they closely corre-
spond to what would happen if all regions where the same, but subject to random changes
in minimum wage bindingness. But suppose that regions differ exclusively in their initial
dispersion parameters and are subject to a national increase in the minimum wage. One can
show that the effective minimum wages changes differentially across regions, and so do out-
comes such as employment and wages. However, that scenario does not correspond to the
